Thompson Hine's top Cleveland partner leaves for Goodyear spinoff






Print
Email


Alison Grant, The Plain Dealer

	



	



By

	
		
	
		
			
	
		
	
	
	
	
	Alison Grant, The Plain Dealer

The Plain Dealer
 Email the author | Follow on Twitter
on December 31, 2010 at  5:10 PM, updated January 02, 2011 at 10:53 AM









 comments

















April Miller Boise is leaving Thompson Hine to become general counsel for Veyance.FAIRLAWN, Ohio -- April Miller Boise, the first woman to lead a major law firm office in Cleveland, has resigned to become the top in-house attorney for a global rubber products company headquartered in Fairlawn. 
Miller Boise starts Jan. 9 as general counsel for Veyance Technologies, created in 2007 when it was spun off by Goodyear Tire & Rubber Co. and purchased by private equity giant Carlyle Group. 
Veyance -- a reference to the conveyance belts it makes -- has 7,000 employees in a dozen countries, including China, Slovenia, Chile and South Africa. Its industrial belts are in demand in emerging markets with big mining operations. Veyance also makes belts and hoses for the automotive, oil and gas industries. 
James Aronoff, 51, succeeds Miller Boise as partner-in-charge of Thompson Hine's Cleveland office. He had been appointed in October to a newly created position as the office's administrative partner, working alongside Miller Boise. Before that, he was chairman of the firm's real estate capital markets practice. 
Miller Boise, 42, of Cleveland, said she wrestled with the decision to leave. Veyance was a great opportunity, though the timing wasn't perfect given her career at the law firm, she said. She became partner-in-charge just two years ago. 
A Florida company recruited Veyance's previous general counsel and the opening popped up quickly, only weeks ago, Miller Boise said. 
Firm managing partner David Hooker said he was sorry to see her go, but took it as the "ultimate compliment" that she had been hired as chief legal officer of a leading business. 
Miller Boise joined Thompson Hine in 1999 after several years as a deal lawyer on Wall Street. She had returned to her home town of Cleveland after her son was born and she and her then-husband decided they wanted a patch of green to call their own. 
She later divorced, and then remarried in April 2009 to a Thompson Hine partner, David Willbrand. He works in the firm's Cincinnati office, so they have a commuter marriage. Together they have four children. 
Miller Boise was the second African American to lead Thompson Hine's Cleveland office. Paul Harris, the first, was wooed to KeyCorp as general counsel in 2003. 
Miller Boise quickly became a rising star at Thompson Hine, spearheading the women's initiative at all eight offices, chairing the private equity subgroup, serving on high-profile boards and, last year, becoming one of 41 co-chairs driving the campaign to get the Issue 6 county government reform measure on the ballot. 
Meanwhile, she handled complex deals, including the $1.5 billion sale of the Goodyear engineered products division that became Veyance. 
She said familiarity with Veyance was one reason she switched jobs. She also was drawn to the company's international footprint, strong management team and the industry itself. 
"I have just always loved manufacturing," she said, "looking at how products are developed and researched and ultimately manufactured and pushed out." 
Although general counsel jobs are usually thought to be less frenetic than firm work, Miller Boise said she doesn't anticipate slowing down. In fact, she expects the demands on her time to be even greater. 
She will rack up lots of travel at the outset as she visits plants scattered worldwide. Veyance has several hundred administrative and back-office employees at its Fairlawn headquarters and two plants in Ohio, in Marysville and St. Marys. 
Miller Boise said she will have to scale back her board work because of her new responsibilities. She is a director at University Hospitals, the Cleveland Museum of Art, Team NEO, the Cuyahoga Community College Foundation and the Citizens Bank/Charter One Joint Regional Advisory Board. 
